      "bodyTr": "Foreign visitors to South Korea in the first quarter of this year reached 4.76 million, marking the highest first-quarter record on file. This represents a 23 percent increase compared to the same period last year. The Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism attributed this growth to the global popularity of Korean culture. The BTS concert at Gwanghwamun Plaza last month is believed to have played a significant role.\n\nThe phenomenon of Korean culture serving as a driving force for Korean tourism has become increasingly pronounced in recent years. A 2024 survey by the Korea Culture and Tourism Institute found that the top reason foreign visitors became interested in Korea was Korean Wave content, followed by traditional Korean culture. What is encouraging is that this interest is expanding beyond Seoul to provincial regions with diverse traditional cultural heritage.\n\nAccording to ministry data, foreign visitors entering through provincial airports in the first quarter surged 50 percent year-over-year. Many tourists using provincial airports have begun turning their attention to regional tourism. In the first quarter, the regional visitation rate among foreign tourists was 34.5 percent, up 3 percentage points from the previous year, while the duration of stays in regions and credit card spending within regions jumped 36 percent and 27 percent, respectively. Though it may be premature to say that the nature of foreign tourism in Korea has fundamentally changed structurally, it is certainly encouraging that foreigners are venturing into regions, staying longer, and spending more.\n\nPresident Lee Jae-myung's remarks at a Cabinet meeting on the 14th about bringing together local residents, self-employed business owners, and tourism activists while having administrative agencies support these efforts appear aimed at nurturing this trend. Accordingly, the Ministry of Public Administration and Security has proposed establishing public-private tourism councils at the city, county, and district levels, while the Culture Ministry has expressed its commitment to supporting regional tourism activists. The direction of public-private cooperation to actively leverage private sector ideas is sound.\n\nHowever, for this to translate into results, local administrative efficiency must be assured in matters concerning transportation, infrastructure, and regulations, and political logic that impedes efficient decision-making must be excluded. Tourism is now one of the most promising solutions to address one of South Korea's most pressing problems: regional depopulation and the widening gap between the Seoul metropolitan area and non-metropolitan regions. We must properly capitalize on the opportunity created by the surge in foreign visitors driven by Korean culture.",
